data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** The syntax is straightforward:

```csharp
Span<nint> nints = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> nuints = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

This works without `unsafe` context (since C# 7.2+ allows `stackalloc` into a `Span<T>`). Each element is 8 bytes on a 64-bit platform (or 4 bytes on 32-bit). The only caveat is that `sizeof(nint)` itself requires an `unsafe` block — but you can use `IntPtr.Size` instead.
